Supplemental Information

Group, Sex, Age, and Order Effects

Although group, sex, age, and trial order effects within the Before Sensors time point were not the primary focus of this study, their inclusion in our models as interaction terms (Group Ã Time Point) or covariates (sex, age, trial order) allowed us to examine these variables.

Group Effects. PwPD demonstrated robustly smaller AAVSs (Î² = -.29, pd = 100%, CI = [-.48, -.08]) compared to control speakers at the baseline Before Sensors condition, after adjusting for age, sex, and articulation rate. Conversely, PwPD and control speakers showed comparable articulation rates (Î² = .04, pd = 57%, CI = [-.39, .46]), M1 (/s/: Î² = -.30, pd = 83%, CI = [-.93, .31]; /Ê/: Î² = -.05, pd = 57%, CI = [-.56, .48]) and M2 values (/s/: Î² = .06, pd = 70%, CI = [-.18, .31]; /Ê/: Î² = -.05, pd = 59%, CI = [-.55, .46]), intelligibility ratings (Î² = -.27, pd = 81%, CI = [-.90, .35]) and naturalness ratings (Î² = -.61, pd = 96%, CI = [-1.31, .10]) at the baseline Before Sensors condition.

Sex Effects. Female speakers demonstrated robustly larger AAVSs (Î² = .31, pd = 100%, CI = [.14, .49]) and higher M1 and M2 values for /s/ (M1: Î² = .80, pd = 100%, CI = [.27, 1.33]; M2: Î² = .24, pd = 99%, CI = [.03, .46]) compared to male speakers, after adjusting for age, group, and articulation rate. Male and female speakers did not robustly differ in their articulation rates (Î² = -.33, pd = 95%, CI = [-.71, .06]), M1 or M2 values for /Ê/ (M1: Î² = .36, pd = 94%, CI = [-.11, .81]; M2: Î² = .35, pd = 94%, CI = [-.09, .80]), intelligibility ratings (Î² = .30, pd = 85%, CI = [-.27, .87]), or naturalness ratings (Î² = .32, pd = 84%, CI = [-.33, .95]).

Age Effects. Older speakers were perceived to be less intelligible (Î² = -.03, pd = 99%, CI = [-.06, -.004]) and natural (Î² = -.03, pd = 98%, CI = [-.06, -.003]), and demonstrated reduced M1 values for /s/ (Î² = -.03, pd = 99%, CI = [-.06, -.004]) in the Before Sensors time point, after adjusting for group, sex, and articulation rate. In contrast, age did not robustly impact articulation rate (Î² = -.02, pd = 97%, CI = [-.04, .001]), AAVS (Î² = -.003, pd = 73%, CI = [-.01, .01]), M1 for /Ê/ (Î² = -.02, pd = 97%, CI = [-.04, .0003]), or M2 measures (/s/: Î² = -.0003, pd = 53%, CI = [-.01, .01]; /Ê/: Î² = -.02, pd = 97%, CI = [-.04, .00003]).

Trial Order Effects. For the perceptual measures, trial order had no robust impact on listenersâ intelligibility ratings (Î² = -.01, pd = 97%, CI = [-.02, .0004]). However, listeners systematically rated samples as less natural the later they were presented in the perceptual experiment (Î² = -.01, pd = 99%, CI = [-.03, -.002]). This tendency was consistent across both groups, regardless of the speakerâs sex or age.
